(383, 21, 0, '<div class="level2">\r\n<p>General event.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Undefined'),
(384, 21, 1, '<p>There is an incoming phone call. Usually a caller ID node just sends out numerical information. A database event can follow (later) that contains the real text information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phone calls are reported in the following form</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nfrom,to</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>where from is the originating number and to is the receiving phone. Numbers is preferable presented in an international form. So a call from England to a Swedish phone should take the following form</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n44-123-1122334,46-657-413430</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>which is sent in tree frames. Some device can&#39;t separate country and area-code and therefore the form</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n441231122334,46657413430</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>will also be valid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a database connected application can later resolve this and present</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nA customer,Eurosource</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the type=8 event, database info, (see below). Note that the comma cant be used in the descriptive names.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Calls from unlisted numbers are presented as</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n,to </pre>', 'Incoming call'),
(385, 21, 2, '<p>There is an outgoing phone call.</p>', 'Outgoing call'),
(386, 21, 3, '<p>This is a event indicating that there is a &ldquo;ring&rdquo; for this call.</p>', 'Ring'),
(387, 21, 4, '<p>The call has been answered.</p>', 'Answer'),
(388, 21, 5, '<p>The call has been terminated by the receiving end.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="table sectionedit13">\r\n<table class="inline">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>0</td>\r\n			<td>An ID for the call. This can for instance be a number that increases by one for each call.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 'Hangup'),
(389, 21, 6, '<p>The call has been terminated by the originating end. byte</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="table sectionedit15">\r\n<table class="inline">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>0</td>\r\n			<td>An ID for the call. This can for instance be a number that increases by one for each call.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 'Giveup'),
(390, 21, 7, '<p>The call has been transferred. byte</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="table sectionedit17">\r\n<table class="inline">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>0</td>\r\n			<td>An ID for the call. This can for instance be a number that increases by one for each call.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 'Transfer'),
(391, 21, 8, '<table class="inline">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>0</td>\r\n			<td>Id for the call. This is a number that is increased by one for each call. In this case the number is the same as for the incoming or outgoing events.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1</td>\r\n			<td>Index of phone event (base=0). Each call can be broken up into fragments. This is the fragment number.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2</td>\r\n			<td>Total number of events (fragments) for this call information.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3-7</td>\r\n			<td>Caller information. Real text information.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Database Info'),
(392, 22, 0, '<div class="level2">\r\n<p>General event.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Undefined'),
(393, 22, 1, '<p>Clear the display on displays in a certain zone,sub-zone.</p>', 'Clear Display'),
(394, 22, 2, '<p>Move the cursor to a specific position on displays in a certain zone,sub-zone.</p>', 'Position cursor'),
(395, 22, 3, '<p>Write to display(s) in a certain zone,sub-zone. The update of the display is immediate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Index is increased by one for each event that builds up a specific event. If needed an empty (no data) can be sent as the last event else sending data to fill the display buffer will give the end automatically.</p>', 'Write Display'),
(396, 22, 4, '<p>Write to the buffers of displays in a certain zone,sub-zone. The update of the display is is not done right away but is instead done when the Show Buffer event is received by the display unit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Index is increased by one for each event that builds up a specific event. If needed an empty (no data) can be sent as the last event else sending data to fill the display buffer will give the end automatically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many LCD displays allow definition of special characters. Use this event to define custom matrices buy defining a sub-zone for the user defined matrix(es).</p>', 'Write Display buffer'),
(397, 22, 5, '<p>Tells displays in a certain zone,sub-zone to display the content in their display buffers. The update of the display is immediate.</p>', 'Show Display Buffer'),
(398, 22, 6, '<p>With this call a display buffer parameter can be sent to a display. This parameter is inserted at the escape position %pn in the string in the buffer *when the buffer is transferred to the display*.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that there are no zone and sub-zone defined for this event and the escapes must instead be chosen to be distinct in a system. This means that &amp;p1 will be unique within a system and updating this parameter will update on all displays that has it defined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that the event have one byte less then standard measurement events so all coding types can not be used.</p>', 'Set Display Buffer Parameter'),
(399, 22, 32, '<p>This event contains information that should be displayed on displays pointed out by zone/sub-zone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This event can have the same functionality as Write Display or be set on an higher abstraction level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Index is increase by one for each event that builds up a specific event. If needed an empty (no data) can be sent as the last event else sending data to fill the display buffer will give the end automatically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The text sent to a node can contain escape characters that themselves display data or other display events. Se the new_york node for examples of this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For a multi line display one can use different sub-zones o address different lines. One can also us macro characters to map display events to a line.</p>', 'Show Text'),
(400, 22, 48, '<p>This event contains information that should be displayed on LED(s) pointed out by zone/sub-zone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blink period can be omitted if not used or if blink period is defined hard.</p>', 'Set LED'),
(401, 22, 49, '<p>This event set the color for LED(s) pointed out by zone/sub-zone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If multi-byte resolution for the colors is needed use index to address the byte where 0 means the MSB byte, 1 MSB+1 byte etc (Big endian).</p>', 'Set RGB Color'),
(402, 23, 0, '<p>Undefined</p>', 'Undefined'),
(403, 23, 1, '<p>A RC5 remote code. [<a class="urlextern" href="http://www.xs4all.nl/%7Esbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm" rel="nofollow" title="http://www.xs4all.nl/~sbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm">http://www.xs4all.nl/~sbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm</a> ]Use the VSCP abstract remote format if possible.</p>', 'RC5 Send/Receive'),
(404, 23, 3, '<p>A SONY remote code. [<a class="urlextern" href="http://www.xs4all.nl/%7Esbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm]" rel="nofollow" title="http://www.xs4all.nl/~sbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm]">http://www.xs4all.nl/~sbp/knowledge/ir/sirc.htm]</a> Use the VSCP abstract remote format if possible.</p>', 'SONY 12-bit Send/Receive'),
(405, 23, 32, '<p>Packed LIRC codes code. LRC Codes are normally sent as 64-bit codes or even larger codes. Only codes with a length less then 56 bits (7-bytes) are supported by VSCP and the most significant byte of the LIRC code is not transferred. <a class="urlextern" href="http://www.lirc.org/" rel="nofollow" title="http://www.lirc.org/">http://www.lirc.org/</a></p>', 'LIRC (Linux Infrared Remote Control)'),
(406, 23, 48, '<p>Instead of sending codes that relates to a certain remote this format is general. And therefore more flexible</p>', 'VSCP Abstract Remote Format'),
(407, 23, 49, '<p>Instead of sending codes that relates to a certain remote this format is general. And therefore more flexible.</p>', 'MAPito Remote Format'),
